[{"id":42078,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$2\\%$","$3\\%$","$6\\%$","$4\\%$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Bulk modulus is given by $B = \\dfrac{\\Delta P}{-\\dfrac{\\Delta V}{V}}$<br><br>The fractional decrease in volume is $-\\dfrac{\\Delta V}{V} = \\dfrac{\\Delta P}{B}$<br><br>Substituting the given values:<br><br>$-\\dfrac{\\Delta V}{V} = \\dfrac{6.3 \\times 10^7}{2.1 \\times 10^9} = 3 \\times 10^{-2}$<br><br>The percentage decrease in volume is $\\left(-\\dfrac{\\Delta V}{V}\\right) \\times 100$<br><br>Percentage decrease $= 3 \\times 10^{-2} \\times 100 = 3\\%$<br><br>Answer: $3\\%$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42182,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$\\ell / 2$","$\\ell$","$2 \\ell$","zero"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":42095,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["(A)-(IV), (B)-(II), (C)-(III), (D)-(I)","(A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)-(I), (D)-(II)","(A)-(II), (B)-(IV), (C)-(I), (D)-(III)","(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(II), (D)-(IV)"],"answer":1,"solution":"(1) stress $=\\frac{F_{\\text {restoring }}}{A}$\nIf $\\mathrm{A}=1$\nStress $=F_{\\text {restoring }}$\n(A)-(III)\n(2)<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/MBXI-76aDG5GkDVht5jNZPT9lkqbIB7_SsPktIf9JtU.original.fullsize.png\"><br />(B)-(IV)\n(3)<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7NFE3WRFDhA_FQKy6_lRInzuZkghDIRP0plkfqb3Tsk.original.fullsize.png\"><br />(C)-(I)\n(4)<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/USk5Xj11TYZZ9lBycPn4WOL6XS2l3QRx5ELwwekcoB8.original.fullsize.png\"><br />(D)-(II)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42101,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Bulk modulus is given by, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mo>∆</mo><mi>P</mi></mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><mi>V</mi></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mo>∆</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>B</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><mi>V</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>ρ</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>B</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><mi>V</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>×</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>×</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn></mrow><mn>100</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>18</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42072,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$1.1$","$2.22$","$1.21$","$4.44$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given that the wires have equal cross-sectional area $A$ and are under the same tension $F$, the elongation $\\Delta L$ is given by:<br><br>$\\Delta L = \\dfrac{F L}{A Y}$<br><br>Since the elongations in both wires are equal ($\\Delta L_A = \\Delta L_B$):<br><br>$\\dfrac{F L_A}{A Y_A} = \\dfrac{F L_B}{A Y_B}$<br><br>$\\dfrac{L_A}{Y_A} = \\dfrac{L_B}{Y_B}$<br><br>$L_B = L_A \\times \\dfrac{Y_B}{Y_A}$<br><br>Substituting the given values $L_A = 2.2$ m and $\\dfrac{Y_A}{Y_B} = \\dfrac{20}{11}$:<br><br>$L_B = 2.2 \\times \\dfrac{11}{20}$<br><br>$L_B = \\dfrac{24.2}{20} = 1.21$ m<br><br>Answer: $1.21$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42179,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$0.16 \\%$","$0.32 \\%$","$0.08 \\%$","$0.24 \\%$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given: $F=100 \\mathrm{kN}=10^5 \\mathrm{~N}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{Y}=2 \\times 10^{11} \\mathrm{Nm}^{-2} \\\\\n& \\ell_0=1.0 \\mathrm{~m}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nradius $\\mathrm{r}=10 \\mathrm{~mm}=10^{-2} \\mathrm{~m}$\nFrom formula, $Y=\\frac{\\text { Stress }}{\\text { Strain }}$\n$$\n\\Rightarrow \\quad \\text { Strain }=\\frac{\\text { Stress }}{Y}=\\frac{F}{A Y}\n$$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& =\\frac{10^5}{\\pi r^2 Y}=\\frac{10^5}{3.14 \\times 10^{-4} \\times 2 \\times 10^{11}} \\\\\n& =\\frac{1}{628}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nTherefore $\\%$ strain $=\\frac{1}{628} \\times 100=0.16 \\%$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":42120,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>77</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>As we know,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>F</mi><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>A</mi><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow><mi>l</mi></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><mi>l</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></math></p><p>For both cases force applied is the same, therefore</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mi>A</mi><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow><mi>l</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mi>A</mi><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow><mi>l</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42136,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/08e890c3-7479-4415-9a6e-61ec9174973d-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 161px;\" /></p><p>From the above graph, we can find that when the strain is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;the stress is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MPa</mi></math>. We know that energy density is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>stress</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>strain</mi></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kJ</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42070,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$1.0 \\times 10^{11}$","$2.0 \\times 10^{10}$","$1.0 \\times 10^{10}$","$2.0 \\times 10^{11}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"From the given graph, we can observe that for a load $W = 20$ N, the extension is $\\Delta l = 2 \\times 10^{-4}$ m.<br><br>The formula for Young's modulus $Y$ is:<br><br>$Y = \\dfrac{\\text{Stress}}{\\text{Strain}} = \\dfrac{W / A}{\\Delta l / L} = \\dfrac{W L}{A \\Delta l}$<br><br>Given:<br>Length of the wire, $L = 1$ m<br>Cross-sectional area, $A = 10^{-5}$ m$^2$<br><br>Substituting the values into the formula:<br><br>$Y = \\dfrac{20 \\times 1}{10^{-5} \\times 2 \\times 10^{-4}}$<br><br>$Y = \\dfrac{20}{2 \\times 10^{-9}}$<br><br>$Y = 10 \\times 10^9 = 1.0 \\times 10^{10}$ N/m$^2$<br><br>Answer: $1.0 \\times 10^{10}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42108,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>l</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Young&#39;s modulus is same for both the wires since the material is same.</p><p>For the first wire,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>f</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>For the second wire,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>l</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Dividing (i) by (ii)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>f</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>l</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>f</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>l</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42082,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["2","1","4","5"],"answer":3,"solution":"Young's modulus: $Y = \\frac{\\sigma}{\\epsilon} = \\frac{F/A}{\\Delta L/L}$.<br>When the same force is applied and both wires stretch by the same extension $\\Delta L$, the ratio of Young's moduli is:<br>$\\frac{Y_A}{Y_B} = \\frac{F/A_A}{\\Delta L/L_A} \\times \\frac{\\Delta L/L_B}{F/A_B} = \\frac{A_B}{A_A} \\times \\frac{L_A}{L_B}$ <br>$=\\frac{4.5 \\times 10^{-5}}{3.0 \\times 10^{-5}} \\times \\frac{6.0}{5.4} = 1.5 \\times \\frac{10}{9} = \\frac{5}{3}$.<br>Therefore $x : 3 = 5 : 3$, giving $x = 5$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42115,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The data given is</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Using the equation</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow><mi>A</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi><mi>A</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>22</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>7</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>49</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>22</mn></mrow><mn>10</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>49</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>22</mn></mrow><mn>98</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kg</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42097,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & 3=\\mathrm{K}(\\mathrm{a}-\\ell) \\\\ & 2=\\mathrm{K}(\\mathrm{b}-\\ell) \\\\ & \\mathrm{T}=\\mathrm{K}(3 \\mathrm{a}-2 \\mathrm{~b}-\\ell) \\\\ & \\mathrm{T}=\\mathrm{K}(3(\\mathrm{a}-\\ell)-2(\\mathrm{~b}-\\ell) \\\\ & =\\mathrm{K}\\left[3\\left(\\frac{3}{\\mathrm{~K}}\\right)-2\\left(\\frac{2}{\\mathrm{~K}}\\right)\\right] \\\\ & =9-4 \\\\ & =5 \\mathrm{~N}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42128,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The wire is stretched to&nbsp;double its length. Therefore, if the length of the wore was&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math>, change in the length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>l</mi></math>.</p><p>Applying Hooke&#39;s law,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mtext>stress</mtext><mtext>strain</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mi>A</mi><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow><mi>l</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>Y</mi><mi>A</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>11</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>11</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow><mi>l</mi></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42132,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Since breaking stress (Maximum lifting capacity) is the property of material, so it will remain same.</p><p>Now, breaking stress<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Maximum</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>lifting</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>capacity</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Area</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cross</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>section</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>rope</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>25</mn><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>625</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42133,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f1018461-1cf0-43cf-87b3-73a82210dbbf-image.png\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 144px;\" /></p><p>Tension at a distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> from lower end <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow><mi>l</mi></mfrac><mi>x</mi></math></p><p>If the elongation in the element is taken as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>d</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;then, using Hooke&#39;s law,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>d</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>d</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>Y</mi></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow></msubsup><mo>d</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>l</mi></msubsup><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>Y</mi></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>A</mi><mi>Y</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>20</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>11</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42144,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>In series combination,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>&#8467;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>&#8467;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>Y</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mi>&#8467;</mi><mi>Y</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Equivalent length of rod after joining is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#8467;</mi></math></p><p>As, lengths are same and force is also same in series</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#916;</mi><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mi>eq</mi></msub><msub><mi>Y</mi><mi>eq</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#8467;</mi><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>&#8467;</mi><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#8467;</mi></mrow><mi>Y</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#8467;</mi><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>&#8467;</mi><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42183,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$2 S^2 Y$","$S^2 / 2 Y$","$2 Y / S^2$","$S / 2 Y$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$U=\\frac{1}{2}$ stress $\\times$ strain $=\\frac{S^2}{2 Y}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":42079,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$3$","$2$","$1.9$","$1$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Given:<br>Length of string A, $L_A = 0.314$ m<br>Young's modulus of string A, $Y_A = 2 \\times 10^{10}$ N/m$^2$<br>Radius of both strings, $r = 0.2$ mm $= 2 \\times 10^{-4}$ m<br>Length of string B, $L_B = 2L_A = 0.628$ m<br>Young's modulus of string B, $Y_B = 2Y_A = 4 \\times 10^{10}$ N/m$^2$<br>Mass of load, $m = 0.8$ kg<br>Acceleration due to gravity, $g = 10$ m/s$^2$<br><br>Tension in both strings, $T = mg = 0.8 \\times 10 = 8$ N<br><br>Cross-sectional area of both strings:<br>$A = \\pi r^2 = 3.14 \\times (2 \\times 10^{-4})^2 = 3.14 \\times 4 \\times 10^{-8}$ m$^2$<br><br>Elongation in string A:<br>$\\Delta L_A = \\dfrac{T L_A}{A Y_A}$<br>$\\Delta L_A = \\dfrac{8 \\times 0.314}{3.14 \\times 4 \\times 10^{-8} \\times 2 \\times 10^{10}}$<br>$\\Delta L_A = \\dfrac{8 \\times 0.314}{8 \\times 3.14 \\times 10^2} = \\dfrac{0.1}{10^2} = 10^{-3}$ m $= 1$ mm<br><br>Elongation in string B:<br>$\\Delta L_B = \\dfrac{T L_B}{A Y_B}$<br>$\\Delta L_B = \\dfrac{8 \\times (2 \\times 0.314)}{A \\times (2 Y_A)} = \\dfrac{T L_A}{A Y_A} = 1$ mm<br><br>Net change in length of the combination:<br>$\\Delta L = \\Delta L_A + \\Delta L_B = 1 + 1 = 2$ mm<br><br>Answer: $2$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42173,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["Young's modulii <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mo>&lt;</mo> </math> shear modulii <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mo>&lt;</mo> </math> bulk modulii","Bulk modulii <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mo>&lt;</mo> </math> shear modulii <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mo>&lt;</mo> </math> Young's modulii","Shear modulii <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mo>&lt;</mo> </math> Young's modulii <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mo>&lt;</mo> </math> bulk modulii","Bulk modulii <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mo>&lt;</mo> </math> Young's modulii <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mo>&lt;</mo> </math> shear modulii"],"answer":2,"solution":"For aluminium and copper magnitude of Shear modulii is less than Young's modulii and bulk modulii is maximum.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":42073,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given parameters:<br>$L = 3\\text{ m}$<br>$\\Delta L = 3 \\times 10^{-3}\\text{ m}$<br>$V = 600 \\times 10^{-6}\\text{ m}^3$<br>$Y = 1.1 \\times 10^{11}\\text{ N/m}^2$<br><br>Strain is given by:<br>$\\text{Strain} = \\dfrac{\\Delta L}{L} = \\dfrac{3 \\times 10^{-3}}{3} = 10^{-3}$<br><br>Elastic potential energy stored in the wire is:<br>$U = \\dfrac{1}{2} \\times \\text{Stress} \\times \\text{Strain} \\times \\text{Volume}$<br><br>Since $\\text{Stress} = Y \\times \\text{Strain}$:<br>$U = \\dfrac{1}{2} \\times Y \\times (\\text{Strain})^2 \\times V$<br><br>Substituting the values:<br>$U = \\dfrac{1}{2} \\times (1.1 \\times 10^{11}) \\times (10^{-3})^2 \\times (600 \\times 10^{-6})$<br><br>$U = \\dfrac{1}{2} \\times 1.1 \\times 10^{11} \\times 10^{-6} \\times 600 \\times 10^{-6}$<br><br>$U = \\dfrac{1}{2} \\times 1.1 \\times 600 \\times 10^{-1}$<br><br>$U = \\dfrac{1}{2} \\times 66 = 33\\text{ J}$<br><br>Answer: $33$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42076,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given:<br>Side length of the cube, $L = 5$ cm $= 0.05$ m<br>Modulus of rigidity, $\\eta = 10^5$ N/m$^2$<br>Force applied on the upper face, $F = 10$ N<br><br>Area of the upper face, $A = L^2 = (0.05)^2 = 2.5 \\times 10^{-3}$ m$^2$<br><br>Shear stress is given by:<br>$\\text{Stress} = \\dfrac{F}{A} = \\dfrac{10}{2.5 \\times 10^{-3}} = 4000$ N/m$^2$<br><br>Shear strain is given by:<br>$\\text{Strain} = \\dfrac{\\Delta x}{L}$<br><br>Modulus of rigidity is defined as the ratio of shear stress to shear strain:<br>$\\eta = \\dfrac{\\text{Stress}}{\\text{Strain}} = \\dfrac{F/A}{\\Delta x/L}$<br><br>Rearranging for displacement $\\Delta x$:<br>$\\Delta x = \\dfrac{F \\cdot L}{A \\cdot \\eta}$<br><br>Substituting the values:<br>$\\Delta x = \\dfrac{10 \\times 0.05}{2.5 \\times 10^{-3} \\times 10^5}$<br><br>$\\Delta x = \\dfrac{0.5}{250} = 0.002$ m<br><br>Converting to millimeters:<br>$\\Delta x = 0.002 \\times 1000 = 2$ mm<br><br>Answer: $2$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42180,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$O A$","$O C$","$O D$","$O B$"],"answer":0,"solution":"From the graph, it is clear that for the same value of load, elongation is maximum for wire $O A$. Hence $O A$ is the thinnest wire among the four wires.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)",