>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>125</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Tension in the string <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></mfrac><mi>g</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Stress <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>T</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>24</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mn>48</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>015625</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42176,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$1.0 \\times 10^{-4}$","$1.5 \\times 10^{-4}$","$0.25 \\times 10^{-4}$","$5 \\times 10^{-4}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given, $y=2 \\times 10^{11} \\mathrm{Nm}^{-2}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { Stress }\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{F}}{\\mathrm{A}}\\right)=5 \\times 10^7 \\mathrm{Nm}^{-2} \\\\\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{V}=0.02 \\%=2 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{~m}^3 \\\\\n& \\frac{\\Delta \\mathrm{r}}{\\mathrm{r}}=?\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\gamma=\\frac{\\text { stress }}{\\text { strain }} \\Rightarrow \\operatorname{strain}\\left(\\frac{\\Delta \\ell}{\\ell_0}\\right)=\\frac{\\gamma}{\\text { stress }} \\\\\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{V}=2 \\pi \\mathrm{r} \\ell_0 \\Delta \\mathrm{r}-\\pi \\mathrm{r}^2 \\Delta \\ell\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nFrom eqns (i) and (ii) putting the value of $\\Delta \\ell, \\ell_0$ and $\\Delta \\mathrm{V}$ and solving we get\n$$\n\\frac{\\Delta \\mathrm{r}}{\\mathrm{r}}=0.25 \\times 10^{-4}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":42151,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow><mi>&#961;</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>P</mi></mrow><mi>K</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow><mi>P</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>K</mi><mrow><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>P</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>M</mi><mi>V</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>&#961;</mi></mrow><mi>&#961;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow><mi>V</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>P</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow><mi>V</mi></mfrac></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow><mi>V</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>P</mi><mi>k</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>&#961;</mi></mrow><mi>&#961;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>P</mi><mi>k</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>P</mi></mrow><mi>k</mi></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42074,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["increases by two times","reduces by half","remains unchanged","becomes one fourth"],"answer":2,"solution":"Young's modulus $Y$ is an intrinsic property of the material of the wire.<br><br>It depends only on the nature of the material and its temperature, and is independent of the dimensions of the wire such as length $L$ and radius $r$.<br><br>Therefore, when the radius and length of the steel wire are doubled, its Young's modulus remains unchanged.<br><br>Answer: remains unchanged","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42178,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$50 \\mathrm{~kg}$","$400 \\mathrm{~kg}$","$100 \\mathrm{~kg}$","$200 \\mathrm{~kg}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Breaking force $\\alpha$ area of cross section of wire\nLoad hold by wire is independent of length of the wire.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null}]